        <hr noshade size="2" color="#545A7D">
        
         Straight percentages work well for spells and taxes.  They are self-scaling, and the true effectiveness of a spell depends more upon the level it is received, not the level that you get enhancement fo it.  Enhancing an older spell, for example, will never make it better than an improvement from a later version of the spell.  Here's an example of damage scaling:</P><P>30% of 100 damage.... 30 point increase<BR>30% of 1000 damage... 300 point increase</P><P>You really can't compare this directly to melee haste, anyway.  I don't see the connection, since melee haste has one simple effect and the focus items have several various effects beyond damage increase.</P><P>Xandain Ashdale, 54 Heretic<a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height="15" width="15" border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
